item.text: A place to declare values that cannot be created using FHIRPath such as Coding. Retrieve the following items has answer value using variable expression, to use the declared value.
Observation ID of Mood Rating Session 4 Score

Tip #1
The purpose of the Mood Rating Scale is to help clients sort through what happens in their lives that affect their mood.

Tip #2
Help the client make the explicit link between mood and events.

Example dialogue
"Let's check in on how you have been feeling."
On a scale of 1 to 10, with 1 being the worst mood and 10 being the best mood, how have you been feeling since the last time I saw you?

Summarize assessment scores and link to life events

extension.valueString: Summarize assessment scores and link to life events

item.text:
Tip #1
Note that these assessments consist of screening tools, so their scores are not diagnostic.

Tip #2
Link the client's symptoms to their life events and daily functioning. For example, you can say: "Scoring a 10 on the PHQ-9 may mean that your symptoms are interfering and causing difficulties in how you manage everyday tasks."
This suggests your symptoms likely fall in the following category:
This suggests your symptoms likely fall in the following category:
This suggests your symptoms likely fall in the following category:
Use this session's scores to determine next steps

Tip #1
If the client primarily presents with symptoms of depression, use their PHQ-9 score in this session to determine next steps:

  •  If none-to-minimal (4 or below), offer a one-month follow-up

  •  If mild (5 to 9, inclusive), offer the option for referral to clinical care and a one-month follow-up

  •  If moderate-to-severe (10 or above), offer referral to clinical care and a one-month follow-up

Tip #2
If the client primarily presents with symptoms of anxiety, use their GAD-7 score in this session to determine next steps:

  •  If none-to-minimal (4 or below), offer a one-month follow-up

  •  If mild (5 to 9, inclusive), offer the option for referral to clinical care and a one-month follow-up

  •  If moderate-to-severe (10 or above), offer referral to clinical care and a one-month follow-up

Tip #3
If the client primarily presents with symptoms of trauma, use their Short-Form PCL score in this session to determine next steps:

  •  If 4 or below, offer a one-month follow-up

  •  If 5 or above, offer referral to clinical care and a one-month follow-up

Tip #4
Offer the client a one-month follow-up regardless of the their assessment results in IPC termination.
Please select how you would like to proceed with the client:
Proceed with IPC termination and schedule a follow-up meeting
Proceed with IPC termination, provide the option for referral to clinical care, and schedule a follow-up meeting
"How do you feel about the work we have done together?"
How do you feel about today being our last session together?
Your assessment scores suggest that you may benefit from a different type of care to help better address your symptoms. You have worked hard. Distress can take time to improve.
After today's session, I can refer you for clinical care if you would like. How do you feel about that? What are your thoughts?

Tip #1
Review symptoms–how have the client's symptoms changed? Which symptoms improved and which remain?

Tip #2
Show the client graphs of how their symptoms have changed across IPC sessions.

Tip #3
If the client's symptoms have not improved, you may say: "Distress can take time to improve. You have worked hard. We can discuss options to help you feel better."

Example dialogue
"Do you remember what some of your symptoms were when you first came here? Do you remember how you were feeling? How are you feeling now?"
Let's look at your symptom changes. What were your symptoms then and what are they now?
Let's take a look at your PHQ-9 scores across sessions:
Let's take a look at your GAD-7 scores across sessions:
Let's take a look at your Short-Form PCL-5 scores across sessions:
Let's take a look at your Mood Rating scores across sessions:

Tip
Review the problem(s) that brought the client to IPC. Remember that the goals of IPC are to reduce symptoms and address the problem area. Many clients will show a reduction in symptoms but may still be working on the identified problem area (e.g., disagreement with their partner). Explore with the client whether their goals have been met and what more needs to be done.

Example dialogue #1
"Since we first met, your problems have improved. You worked hard to make these changes."

Example dialogue #2
"What changes do you see in your life that are connected to how you are feeling now?"
Do you remember why you came? Let’s talk about how you are managing that problem now.
What do you think you still need to work on regarding that problem?
Let’s talk about what skills you learned here that helped you manage your problem.
Future Planning: Review future situations that may trigger symptoms

Tip #1
Have the client generate their own ideas. If they cannot come up with anything, be prepared to discuss 1-2 future situations you think may trigger their symptoms.

Tip #2
Discuss with the client what skills they can use to manage future situations that may trigger symptoms.
What do you think are some situations that may trigger your symptoms in the future?
Future Planning: Review skills the client found helpful
Review the specific IPC skills the client used to help resolve their identified problem area. If the client cannot come up with anything, be prepared to list some skills to stimulate discussion.
What are some of the skills you learned here that you found useful in coping with your problems? How would you use these skills in future situations?
Future Planning: Review warning signs for the recurrence of symptoms and what the client could do
"How will you recognize if you need to seek help again for your symptoms, and what will you do to find help?"
How would you know if your symptoms are coming back? How would your symptoms and behaviors change?
I am going to provide you with our agency's contact information. You can reach out to us if you think your symptoms are coming back. How does that sound?
Summarize what was discussed in this session, give the client credit for their hard work, remind them to continue using the IPC skills they have learned, and share your final thoughts on termination.
Remember to complete any other recommended interventions before scheduling the one-month follow-up. If this is the client's last session, then proceed to the one-month follow-up scheduling form.
Proceed with IPC termination, provide referral to clinical care, and schedule a follow-up meeting
"How do you feel about the work we have done together?"
How does it make you feel to know that today is our last session together?

Tip #1
Reassure the client that they did not "fail" IPC and help them understand that distress can take longer than 4 sessions to improve.

Tip #2
Facilitate a warm referral by saying: "I can help pass along what we have worked on and what future work you would like to do with your new provider. What would you like to communicate to your new provider?"

Tip #3
Discuss with the client how to overcome potential barriers to engaging in clinical care by asking: "What could get in the way of you attending sessions with a future provider?"

After today's session, I will be referring you for a different type of care to help better address your symptoms. You have worked hard. Distress can take time to improve, or it is possible that a different type of care would work better for you. How do you feel about that? What are your thoughts?
